Anonymous Sun 11 Jul 2021 22:36:59 No.40101753 Report
Quoted By: >>40101796 >>40103029
Frite, I'm not sure if you're around, but if you are I want to tell you Lotus is some of the greatest shit I've read in awhile. I struggle like hell with density; you've got an ear for pacing and I admire the fuck out of that. I also admire your approach to characterisation, especially for fanfiction. The behavior of characters is consistently believable, and Tigress's coming around is remarkably natural especially given the brief time frame involved. Adorable, engaging, and surprisingly funny. Supply me more Tigress.
>Constructive criticism or whatever
If I was going to nit-pick, it would be occasional repetition of specific figurative language. I love the "benign" metaphor and simile approach in which comparisons are drawn to objects and events in daily life, but you occasionally use the same one in rapid succession (say, relating thoughtfulness to clockwork for multiple characters). It makes sense that the speaker would gravitate towards objects and events with which he is familiar, but it might be with a swap or omission here and there.

>>40096172
Your prose is pretty good, Anon! I might suggest cutting your sentences down a little bit, though. I know that's a little rich coming from me, but you use a lot of
>You think
>You feel
>etc
That can probably be avoided. We're in second person, so Anon's perspective might as well be the world. You don't have to tell me that her fur feels soft to me, you can just tell me that it IS soft. You don't have to tell us that we feel the weight of her paw on our backs, you can just tell us that it rests heavily there. Sentences structured that way tend to be more engaging and keep the reader more in the moment, which is important if you're going to be doing a lot of imagery.
>Actually telling a story or whatever
If you struggle coming up with something, my advice would be to just start writing (like you have) and see what starts to happen. You'll have to cut a lot after, but a concept may crystalize.

OK, let's break down a few things into questions. Consider them prompts for paragraphs. In most of my first drafts, each previous paragraph partly answers a question and suggests another. After a while I have characters, and they take over.

How did Anon and the woman meet?
How long have they known each other?
Was last night their first real night together, and bits like how her fur tickles the ears from coincidental contact?
Why is she insecure?
what direction is the light coming from? An east window has a completely different quality than a west window, with north and south depending on the time of year.
What time of year, and where? AC in the morning suggests a summer heatwave, unless she likes it below 70F/20C in the bedroom.
How much stronger is she?

Then what's next...
What is their morning routine? Shower? Food? Turn on the TV or radio for the news?
Who are their neighbors, and what noises are they making?
What's outside? Is it a dense urban area with little wildlife? Is it countryside with deer and heavy tree cover? Is it semi-urban, where certain things like squirrels and small hawks are normal?
Is it a weekend, or a workday?
